text: Can you tell me what kind of things your child likes? What is reinforcing to him/her?
Are there certain foods or games that make your happy or calm?
If yes, describe.
Does your child have favorite TV shows or movies?
If yes, describe.
Are there things you try to avoid doing or saying around, or showing to, your child? Are there things that tend to cause your child distress?
If yes, describe.
What do you normally do if your child becomes very upset? Are people other than you, as the parent, able to calm your child down when he/she is upset?
Does your child exhibit any complex mannerisms or self-injurious behavior?
If yes, describe.
What does your child do when he/she is upset?
Does your child ever hit someone, or bite?
If yes, describe.
What is the primary mode of communication you use with your child (for example, pictures, single words, sentences)? Do you sign with your child at home?
Does your child have any dietary restrictions or food allergies?
If yes, describe.
Does your child have any specific sensory sensitivities?
If yes, what are they?
Does your child have any problems wearing a hat or swim cap?
If yes, describe.
How does your child react to having his/her head touched? How does he/she react to a haircut?
How does your child react to having wet hair?
Does your child wear glasses?
If so, can he/she play computer games or watch movies without them? Describe.
How does your child handle transitions?
Does your child typically nap?
If so, at what times? What happens if he/she misses a nap?
Becomes upset if interrupted in what he/she is doing
Insists on walking in a particular pattern (e.g. straight line)
Insists on sitting at the same place
Dislikes changes in appearance or behavior of the people around him/her
Insists on using a particular door
Likes the same CD, tape, record or piece of music played continually; Likes same movie/video or part of movie/video
Resists changing activities; Difficulty with transitions
Insists on the same routine, household, school or work schedule everyday
Insists that specific things take place at specific times
Fascination, preoccupation with one subject or activity (e.g. trains, computers, weather, dinosaurs)
Strongly attached to one specific object
Preoccupation with part(s) of object rather than the whole object (e.g. buttons on clothes, wheels on toy cars)
Fascination, preoccupation with movement/things that move (e.g. fans, clocks)
